  "body": "It's a special syntax that lets users write stuff like their own versions of stuff like `<before ...>`. (description copied from https://github.com/rakudo/rakudo/issues/1634#issuecomment-374689565)\r\n\r\n> [â€¦] it is the syntax that lets us parse `<before abc>` and similar. Unlike with `<foo: ...>` and `<foo(...)>`, where the args are parsed by the MAIN language, the `<foo ...>` form parses the rest of the assertion using the regex language, wraps it in a closure, and passes it to foo. Thus it's a general syntax for higher-order regex operators - which is just what before/after are.\r\n\r\nI guess maybe somewhere in the \"advanced\" section or grammars is a good place to put this. Just to separate it from all the common syntax novice users might be reading through.",
